04692nam a22006735i 9780292767850DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20141988txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927678507 a10.7560/7274032doi  a(DE-B1597)587870  a(OCoLC)1286806506  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a863.62231 aOrtega, Julio, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGabriel Garcia Marquez and the Powers of Fiction /cJulio Ortega. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2014] 4c©1988  a1 online resource (104 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTexas Pan American Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tExchange System in One Hundred Years of Solitude -- tThe Economy of the Narrative Sign in No One Writes to the Colonel and In Evil Hour -- tIntertextualities: Three Metamorphoses of Myth in The Autumn of the Patriarch -- tThe Ends of the Text: Journalism in the Fiction of Gabriel García Márquez -- tTruth Disguised: Chronicle of a Death (Ambiguously) Foretold -- tThe Solitude of Latin America (Nobel Lecture, 1982) -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTogether with the late Jorge Luis Borges, Gabriel García Márquez, the 1982 Nobel laureate, stands at the pinnacle of Latin American literature. His work, in the words of Julio Ortega, "contains its own 'deconstructive' force—a literary power capable of reshaping natural order and rhetorical tradition in order to 'carnivalize' the Borges' library and allow us to hear the voices—and the laughter—of a culture, that of Latin America." This reshaping force invites us to read the works of García Márquez in a new way, one that bypasses the traditional, inadequate approaches through Latin American politics, history, and "magical realism." In Gabriel García Márquez and the Powers of Fiction, noted scholars Julio Ortega, Ricardo Gutiérrez Mouat, Michael Palencia-Roth, Aníbal González, and Gonzalo Díaz-Migoyo offer English-speaking readers a new approach to García Márquez's work. Their poststructuralist readings focus on the peculiar sign-system, formal configuration, intradiscursivity, and unfolding representation in the novels One Hundred Years of Solitude, No One Writes to the Colonel, In Evil Hour, The Autumn of the Patriarch, and Chronicle of a Death Foretold and in several of the author's short stories. Also included as an appendix is a translation of García Márquez's Nobel Prize acceptance speech, "The Solitude of Latin America."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGarcia Marquez, Gabriel - Criticism and interpretation. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aDíaz-Migoyo, Gonzalo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarcia Márquez, Gabriel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGonzález, Aníbal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGutiérrez Mouat, Ricardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOrtega, Julio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPalencia-Roth, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311074535140uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/72740340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292767850423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292767850/original  a978-3-11-074535-1  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGru